"Tomanek L.","Variation in the heat shock response and its implication for predicting the effect of global climate change on species' biogeographical distribution ranges and metabolic costs",2010,"Journal of Experimental Biology","213","6",,"971","979",,,10.1242/jeb.038034,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77649211464&partnerID=40&md5=ea5b242e0e4ba2b16d74e880f991e843","Center for Coastal Marine Sciences, Department of Biological Sciences, Polytechnic State University, San Luis Obispo CA 93407, United States","Tomanek, L., Center for Coastal Marine Sciences, Department of Biological Sciences, Polytechnic State University, San Luis Obispo CA 93407, United States","The preferential synthesis of heat shock proteins (Hsps) in response to thermal stress [the heat shock response (HSR)] has been shown to vary in species that occupy different thermal environments. A survey of case studies of aquatic (mostly marine) organisms occupying stable thermal environments at all latitudes, from polar to tropical, shows that they do not in general respond to heat stress with an inducible HSR. Organisms that occupy highly variable thermal environments (variations up to >20°C), like the intertidal zone, induce the HSR frequently and within the range of body temperatures they normally experience, suggesting that the response is part of their biochemical strategy to occupy this thermal niche. The highest temperatures at which these organisms can synthesize Hsps are only a few degrees Celsius higher than the highest body temperatures they experience. Thus, they live close to their thermal limits and any further increase in temperature is probably going to push them beyond those limits. In comparison, organisms occupying moderately variable thermal environments (<10°C), like the subtidal zone, activate the HSR at temperatures above those they normally experience in their habitats. They have a wider temperature range above their body temperature range over which they can synthesize Hsps. Contrary to our expectations, species from highly (in comparison with moderately) variable thermal environments have a limited acclimatory plasticity. Due to this variation in the HSR, species from stable and highly variable environments are likely to be more affected by climate change than species from moderately variable environments. © 2010, Published by The Company of Biologists Ltd.","Acclimation; Biogeography; Global climate change; Heat shock proteins; Heat shock response; Intertidal zone; Metabolic costs; Subtidal zone; Transcriptomics","sea water; adaptation; animal; article; climate change; ecosystem; energy metabolism; environment; gene expression profiling; heat shock response; physiological stress; physiology; temperature; Adaptation, Physiological; Animals; Climate Change; Ecosystem; Energy Metabolism; Environment; Gene Expression Profiling; Heat-Shock Response; Seawater; Stress, Physiological; Temperature",,,,,,"Afonso, L.O.B., Hosoya, S., Osborne, J., Gamperl, A.K., Johnson, S., Lack of glucose and hsp70 responses in haddock melanogrammus aeglefinus (L.) subjected to handling and heat shock (2008) Journal of Fish Biology, 72 (1), pp. 157-167. , DOI 10.1111/j.1095-8649.2007.01697.x; Barry, J.P., Baxter, C.H., Sagarin, R.D., Gllman, S.E., Climate-related, long-term faunal changes in a Californlan rocky intertidal community (1995) Science, 267, pp. 672-675; Berger, M.S., Emlet, R.B., Heat-shock response of the upper intertidal barnacle Balanus glandula: Thermal stress and acclimation (2007) Biol. Bull., 212, pp. 232-241; Bosch, T.C.G., Krylow, S.M., Bode, H.R., Steele, R.E., Thermotolerance and synthesis of heat shock proteins: These responses are present in Hydra attenuata but absent Hydra oligactis (1988) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci., 85, pp. 7927-7931. , USA; Brennecke, T., Gellner, K., Bosch, T.C.G., The belt of a stress response in Hydra oligactis is due to reduced Asp70 mRNA stability (1998) European Journal of Biochemistry, 255 (3), pp. 7